context: Uranium metal reacts with almost all non-metal elements (with an exception of the <a0_0><b5_0>noble gases<b5_0/><a0_0/>) and their compounds, with reactivity increasing with temperature. <a1_0><b6_0>Hydrochloric<b6_0/><a1_0/> and nitric acids dissolve uranium, but non-oxidizing acids other than hydrochloric acid attack the element very slowly. When finely divided, it can react with <a4_0><b9_0>cold water<b9_0/><a4_0/>; in air, uranium metal becomes coated with a dark layer of <a2_0><b7_0>uranium oxide<b7_0/><a2_0/>. Uranium in ores is extracted chemically and converted into <a3_0><b8_0>uranium dioxide<b8_0/><a3_0/> or other chemical forms usable in industry.
